192
00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:28.297
or three of them and hit space, 
it'll automatically create 

193
00:09:28.297 --> 00:09:30.562
a heading block at 
level three and so on. 

194
00:09:30.562 --> 00:09:34.621
This is how I always do it. 
It's a really quick and easy way

195
00:09:34.621 --> 00:09:39.839
to create a heading block
on the fly as well.

196
00:09:41.279 --> 00:09:43.100
Images and alt text. 

197
00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:45.665
On the right side of this slide

198
00:09:45.665 --> 00:09:51.103
we have the orange box with 
the little file missing sign

199
00:09:51.103 --> 00:09:53.920
and it says, 
"A purple slug on a red rose."

200
00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:57.120
That text there,
if you're a sighted person,

201
00:09:57.120 --> 00:09:59.392
this is usually
the only time

202
00:09:59.392 --> 00:10:01.040
you'll interact
with alt text

203
00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:04.800
is when a file or an
image can't be found

204
00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:09.779
or the link is missing it'll
show you that little symbol

205
00:10:09.779 --> 00:10:13.680
and show you the alt text
in place of the image.

206
00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:20.320
but images... if you're 
using a screen reader

207
00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:22.959
then that alt text is what
describes the image.

208
00:10:22.959 --> 00:10:27.658
A little tip, quickly:
Don't use images of text.

209
00:10:27.658 --> 00:10:30.084
I see this on Twitter
all the time,

210
00:10:30.084 --> 00:10:32.978
same with Instagram
where people will post

211
00:10:32.978 --> 00:10:35.401
a big picture of text
in order to 

212
00:10:35.401 --> 00:10:38.793
get around the line limit. 

213
00:10:38.793 --> 00:10:40.880
As a result,

214
00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:43.612
unless you're copying
and pasting all that text

215
00:10:43.612 --> 00:10:45.699
and setting it as the
alt text for that image,

216
00:10:45.699 --> 00:10:47.455
which you can do 
and should do 

217
00:10:47.455 --> 00:10:49.090
if you are going to do this. 

218
00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:50.724
Most of the time people don't

219
00:10:50.724 --> 00:10:54.024
and so it just says the
file name of the image.

220
00:10:54.024 --> 00:10:58.678
It doesn't announce 
anything relevant

221
00:10:58.678 --> 00:11:02.173
and so it's 
entirely inaccessible.

222
00:11:02.173 --> 00:11:05.807
All images, in general,
need alt text.

223
00:11:05.807 --> 00:11:08.451
Well, it's tricky. 

224
00:11:08.451 --> 00:11:10.559
They almost always 
need alt text 

225
00:11:10.559 --> 00:11:13.773
because some of them 
can be presentational 

226
00:11:13.773 --> 00:11:17.220
as they discussed 
in the last presentation. 

227
00:11:17.220 --> 00:11:18.942
There are some images 

228
00:11:18.942 --> 00:11:21.279
that don't actually 
carry any meaning.

229
00:11:21.279 --> 00:11:25.200
We say that those 
are presentational.

230
00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.395
Imagine a graphic 
on the side 

231
00:11:27.395 --> 00:11:30.652
that is just a 
decorative element.

232
00:11:30.652 --> 00:11:32.959
You don't need
alt text for those

233
00:11:32.959 --> 00:11:37.279
but unless you're
absolutely positive,

234
00:11:37.279 --> 00:11:39.163
I would recommend
going ahead

235
00:11:39.163 --> 00:11:41.360
and adding the alt text.
If you're not sure,

236
00:11:41.360 --> 00:11:44.720
let's just assume 
adding the alt text is better

237
00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:47.604
unless you're sure. 
When you're doing this 

238
00:11:47.604 --> 00:11:49.166
to write content 
it's almost always 

239
00:11:49.166 --> 00:11:51.839
going to be the 
right choice to add it.

240
00:11:51.839 --> 00:11:56.800
Writing alt text is actually
kind of hard in my opinion.

241
00:11:56.800 --> 00:12:00.800
I wanted to get better at it
so I asked on Twitter,

242
00:12:00.800 --> 00:12:03.370
asked people for 
their favorite tips 

243
00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:05.061
on writing good alt text.

244
00:12:05.061 --> 00:12:07.812
I said it's sometimes
hard for me to find the line

245
00:12:07.812 --> 00:12:10.139
between not enough
and too much description.

246
00:12:10.139 --> 00:12:12.278
I got back
what I felt like

247
00:12:12.278 --> 00:12:17.138
were some good responses
that helped me categorize

248
00:12:17.138 --> 00:12:19.200
how to write better alt text.

249
00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:22.880
Some of them were
to be descriptive but succinct,

250
00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:25.959
about one to three
sentences max.

251
00:12:25.959 --> 00:12:29.795
Highlight the important
details in the image

252
00:12:29.795 --> 00:12:32.880
that are relevant
to the page content.

253
00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:37.040
That's the part that
I had not considered before

254
00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:40.663
is that it needs to be 
relevant to the page content. 

255
00:12:40.663 --> 00:12:43.136
It's not just in 
a standalone image, 

256
00:12:43.136 --> 00:12:44.959
if it's within 
your content.

257
00:12:44.959 --> 00:12:47.615
There's likely a
reason it's there

258
00:12:47.615 --> 00:12:50.423
so try to create 
that connection.

259
00:12:50.423 --> 00:12:53.073
I'd heard recently too
about someone that

260
00:12:53.073 --> 00:12:56.761
tried to relate it to an image
being like paragraph text.

261
00:12:56.761 --> 00:12:58.828
If the image
wasn't there,

262
00:12:58.828 --> 00:13:02.222
that text could be
naturally inserted.

263
00:13:02.222 --> 00:13:05.466
This is something I knew 
but I would still do 

264
00:13:05.466 --> 00:13:09.245
from time to time which is 
starting alt text 

265
00:13:09.245 --> 00:13:12.339
with, "An image of" 
or "A gif of" 

266
00:13:12.339 --> 00:13:16.800
and you don't need 
to do that.

267
00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:18.985
A screen reader
already tells you

268
00:13:18.985 --> 00:13:21.078
that it's an image
and then reads alt text.

269
00:13:21.078 --> 00:13:26.012
There's no reason to do that
but I would still catch myself

270
00:13:26.012 --> 00:13:28.791
trying to write it that way
for some reason.

271
00:13:28.791 --> 00:13:31.326
Carie Fisher did 
this good article 

272
00:13:31.326 --> 00:13:33.545
for Smashing Magazine 
about the telephone 

273
00:13:33.545 --> 00:13:35.878
and one of the things 
she recommended for 

274
00:13:35.878 --> 00:13:38.692
writing good alt text 
was the telephone test. 

275
00:13:38.692 --> 00:13:41.119
This goes back 
to the first slide, 

276
00:13:41.119 --> 00:13:45.279
the broken image slide of the 
purple slug on a red rose.

277
00:13:45.279 --> 00:13:50.526
She said imagine
you're on the telephone

278
00:13:50.526 --> 00:13:53.256
or you pick up a telephone
to call your friend

279
00:13:53.256 --> 00:13:54.808
and as soon 
as they answer

280
00:13:54.808 --> 00:13:56.959
you just say, "A purple slug,"
and hang up.

281
00:13:56.959 --> 00:13:59.964
Well, if you do that
what image do you think

282
00:13:59.964 --> 00:14:02.867
your friend is going to
have in their head?

283
00:14:02.867 --> 00:14:05.440
For me if someone
did that I would just

284
00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:07.669
have a purple slug
in my head

285
00:14:07.669 --> 00:14:09.600
on a white background.

286
00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:11.491
There wouldn't be
any context.

287
00:14:11.491 --> 00:14:14.555
It'd just be this
floating purple slug.

288
00:14:14.555 --> 00:14:17.103
If you compare that
to just adding

289
00:14:17.103 --> 00:14:20.919
a little bit more context
of picking up the phone

290
00:14:20.919 --> 00:14:24.854
and saying, "A purple slug
on a red rose," and hanging up. 

291
00:14:24.854 --> 00:14:28.133
Now for me in 
my mind's eye

292
00:14:28.133 --> 00:14:31.071
I see the purple slug
on the red rose

293
00:14:31.071 --> 00:14:34.160
and then the red rose is
maybe in a field

294
00:14:34.160 --> 00:14:36.818
and so I get like the
rest of the image filled in.

295
00:14:36.818 --> 00:14:39.762
It creates a
fuller image for me.

296
00:14:39.762 --> 00:14:43.970
Those little details
those little extra things,

297
00:14:43.970 --> 00:14:47.242
can make a big difference.

298
00:14:47.242 --> 00:14:50.688
Let's do a little 
practice of it.

299
00:14:50.688 --> 00:14:55.016
You can comment 
on YouTube if you want 

300
00:14:55.016 --> 00:14:58.510
or feel free to 
guess on your own.

301
00:14:58.510 --> 00:15:02.639
Let's select some
alt text for this image here.

302
00:15:02.639 --> 00:15:06.000
I have a little story 
that I start that says,

303
00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.832
I was excited until I sat down
and the small cart shook.

304
00:15:09.832 --> 00:15:12.480
"It will be worth it,"
I reassured myself.

305
00:15:12.480 --> 00:15:15.519
Then we have this image
that we need the alt text for.

306
00:15:15.519 --> 00:15:21.647
There's some mountains, 
the clouds, the little cable cars,

307
00:15:21.647 --> 00:15:25.817
and it's winter.
We got the alpine trees.

308
00:15:25.817 --> 00:15:31.309
It's a nice image
with a bluish cast.

309
00:15:31.309 --> 00:15:34.000
So, let's see. 
Option A. 

310
00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:38.749
Image containing mountains, 
clouds, cable cars, trees. 

311
00:15:38.749 --> 00:15:40.633
Blue and white 
with small houses. 

312
00:15:40.633 --> 00:15:43.519
Photo taken from above.

313
00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:46.955
B. Mountains and tiny cable cars.

314
00:15:46.955 --> 00:15:50.560
We'll talk through
this afterwards.

315
00:15:50.560 --> 00:15:52.518
C. Beautiful view
of the mountains

316
00:15:52.518 --> 00:15:54.000
as we travel
across the land

317
00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.473
in cable cars, 
right before we 

318
00:15:56.473 --> 00:15:58.560
passed through 
the clouds.

319
00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:02.457
D. Cable cars about to travel
underneath the clouds

320
00:16:02.457 --> 00:16:08.971
with large mountains
in the background.

321
00:16:08.971 --> 00:16:14.612
Option A: We have what is
alt text that would be likely

322
00:16:14.612 --> 00:16:18.160
generated by a
stock photo library

323
00:16:18.160 --> 00:16:21.816
when they run an image
through some AI

324
00:16:21.816 --> 00:16:25.759
that just grabs all the 
details it can identify

325
00:16:25.759 --> 00:16:28.101
and shows it into
a text form.

326
00:16:28.101 --> 00:16:32.409
Image containing mountains,
clouds, cable cars, trees,

327
00:16:32.409 --> 00:16:35.609
and all that...
When you go to 

328
00:16:35.609 --> 00:16:37.951
a stock photo library 
and look at their alt text 

329
00:16:37.951 --> 00:16:40.290
almost all of it 
is similar to this

330
00:16:40.290 --> 00:16:42.851
where it's very generic
and gives you

331
00:16:42.851 --> 00:16:45.702
all these little details
but for me even though

332
00:16:45.702 --> 00:16:49.698
you have all the details,
it doesn't give me

333
00:16:49.698 --> 00:16:52.869
a great representation
of the image.

334
00:16:52.869 --> 00:16:57.279
It feels generic
and kind of cold

335
00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:00.761
and so I would not
use that as alt text.

336
00:17:00.761 --> 00:17:03.829
B: Mountains 
and tiny cable cars. 

337
00:17:03.829 --> 00:17:07.957
It's a little short 
but it could work 

338
00:17:07.957 --> 00:17:12.720
but I feel like there's 
a lot that is missing,

339
00:17:12.720 --> 00:17:14.772
C: Beautiful view of 
the mountains 

340
00:17:14.772 --> 00:17:16.482
as we traveled 
across the land

341
00:17:16.482 --> 00:17:20.052
in cable cars right before
we pass through the clouds.

342
00:17:20.052 --> 00:17:23.976
This is tricky because 
if I didn't write this 

343
00:17:23.976 --> 00:17:26.063
select the alt text thing,

344
00:17:26.063 --> 00:17:30.863
I would have a hard time
with these C and D options.

345
00:17:30.863 --> 00:17:34.499
What I think C
does well here is

346
00:17:34.499 --> 00:17:37.777
relates the content
to the image.

347
00:17:37.777 --> 00:17:41.440
It's not just a
standalone alt text.

348
00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:45.094
Similar to D,
D is a great alt text

349
00:17:45.094 --> 00:17:47.803
for this image if it were 

350
00:17:47.803 --> 00:17:52.515
in a slide gallery of images 
or in a stock photo library 

351
00:17:52.515 --> 00:17:54.546
where it's just the image

352
00:17:54.546 --> 00:17:57.847
outside of any
context or content.

353
00:17:57.847 --> 00:18:02.913
C: I would go with C
because it relates 

354
00:18:02.913 --> 00:18:07.695
the text, the content 
to the image better.

355
00:18:07.695 --> 00:18:11.660
D: Cable car is about to 
travel underneath the clouds 

356
00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:14.400
with large mountains 
in the background.

357
00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:16.824
It's still good alt text
but maybe not

358
00:18:16.824 --> 00:18:20.259
the appropriate one within
the context of this story.

359
00:18:20.259 --> 00:18:23.066
So how do we
actually add alt text

360
00:18:23.066 --> 00:18:27.075
in WordPress,
is in the Media Library

361
00:18:27.075 --> 00:18:30.050
in that alternative text field. 

362
00:18:30.050 --> 00:18:33.691
That would actually be 
a great place to 

363
00:18:33.691 --> 00:18:35.200
add that D option

364
00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:38.799
where it was the
stand-alone alt text

365
00:18:38.799 --> 00:18:43.280
that just described 
the image within a gallery.

366
00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:47.760
Because when you add it in the 
Media Library for WordPress,

367
00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:51.600
they're actually isn't any relation 
to existing content in that sense

368
00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:55.470
but then when you're
in the block editor

369
00:18:55.470 --> 00:18:57.682
and you add an image in, 

370
00:18:57.682 --> 00:19:02.417
that is where you would 
give that Option C alt text

371
00:19:02.417 --> 00:19:05.855
where you have you have
the context of it

372
00:19:05.855 --> 00:19:09.269
within the context of 
the story or the content. 

373
00:19:09.269 --> 00:19:12.432
That would be a good place 
to put Option C.

374
00:19:12.432 --> 00:19:15.200
Something to keep in mind
or remember

375
00:19:15.200 --> 00:19:17.985
is that when you add it
to the Image settings,

376
00:19:17.985 --> 00:19:21.266
the alt text there,
it won't save that

377
00:19:21.266 --> 00:19:22.866
to your Media Library.

378
00:19:22.866 --> 00:19:26.460
That alt text within the
Image settings there,

379
00:19:26.460 --> 00:19:29.394
within the block editor,
only saves it

380
00:19:29.394 --> 00:19:33.593
in relation to the
image in the content.

381
00:19:33.593 --> 00:19:36.380
The reason for that is
it's only...

382
00:19:36.380 --> 00:19:40.139
you could add that image again
later on in a story

383
00:19:40.139 --> 00:19:42.175
or on another post
and the context

384
00:19:42.175 --> 00:19:44.559
could be different
and as we've discussed,

385
00:19:44.559 --> 00:19:46.578
it's important to
have the alt text

386
00:19:46.578 --> 00:19:48.160
be in relation
to the content.

387
00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:53.200
But if you add it 
via the Media Library

388
00:19:53.200 --> 00:19:55.637
that's when it would
get used in the gallery

389
00:19:55.637 --> 00:19:57.797
or if you don't
overwrite it here.

390
00:19:57.797 --> 00:20:00.080
I know that's
a little complicated

391
00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:02.073
but it's just something
to try to keep in mind

392
00:20:02.073 --> 00:20:03.670
if you're not sure
why your alt text

393
00:20:03.670 --> 00:20:05.520
is showing up or it's 
showing up differently,

394
00:20:05.520 --> 00:20:07.349
things like that.

395
00:20:07.349 --> 00:20:10.710
That was a bit
about images

396
00:20:10.710 --> 00:20:13.328
and now we
can go to links.

397
00:20:13.328 --> 00:20:17.705
What I mean by
that is the hyperlink,

398
00:20:17.705 --> 00:20:19.286
things like that. 

399
00:20:19.286 --> 00:20:21.832
Something, and I 
see people do

400
00:20:21.832 --> 00:20:25.308
use links inappropriately
all the time...

401
00:20:25.308 --> 00:20:30.078
Some of these, 
they're very little things

402
00:20:30.078 --> 00:20:32.299
a lot of accessibility too.
When you're creating content

403
00:20:32.299 --> 00:20:34.565
it's just doing
the little things right

404
00:20:34.565 --> 00:20:36.768
can make a 
huge difference. 

405
00:20:36.768 --> 00:20:40.416
One thing, don't open links
in a new tab please.

406
00:20:40.416 --> 00:20:43.128
In general, anything
that you code

407
00:20:43.128 --> 00:20:45.859
that takes away
control from the user

408
00:20:45.859 --> 00:20:47.649
is a bad thing.

409
00:20:47.649 --> 00:20:49.242
When you go to a website, 

410
00:20:49.242 --> 00:20:51.919
if you want to open something
in a new tab,

411
00:20:51.919 --> 00:20:54.918
you can [video stutters] 
click or right click

412
00:20:54.918 --> 00:20:56.480
and select open in a new tab.

413
00:20:56.480 --> 00:20:58.907
Those are choices that
the user can make.

414
00:20:58.907 --> 00:21:01.670
When you code it so that 

415
00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:03.280
it automatically opens 
in a new tab,

416
00:21:03.280 --> 00:21:06.400
you're taking that control
away from someone

417
00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:08.364
which is not ideal.

418
00:21:08.364 --> 00:21:10.700
Almost all the time,
the arguments,

419
00:21:10.700 --> 00:21:13.035
I'm sure there is
some valid argument

420
00:21:13.035 --> 00:21:14.799
for opening links
in a new tab,

421
00:21:14.799 --> 00:21:16.619
but generally when I hear them, 

422
00:21:16.619 --> 00:21:19.710
they're more focused 
on the business side of it 

423
00:21:19.710 --> 00:21:22.159
than they are about 
the user preference.

424
00:21:22.159 --> 00:21:24.666
Other issues with 
opening links in a new tab

425
00:21:24.666 --> 00:21:27.084
is that it takes you
out of the context

426
00:21:27.084 --> 00:21:30.284
that you were in and so now 
your back button is broken.

427
00:21:30.284 --> 00:21:32.647
If you didn't notice it
open in a new tab,

428
00:21:32.647 --> 00:21:34.240
you're not sure
where you are.

429
00:21:34.240 --> 00:21:37.159
You might have been...
There's a lot of things

430
00:21:37.159 --> 00:21:39.877
that can go wrong
because of that.

431
00:21:39.877 --> 00:21:42.064
Unless you're
absolutely sure

432
00:21:42.064 --> 00:21:45.280
that it's better accessibility
to have it open in a new tab,

433
00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:48.159
you should not do it.

434
00:21:48.400 --> 00:21:53.716
Like the last talk described,
you need something more

435
00:21:53.716 --> 00:21:58.469
than just the color
to offset your link text.

436
00:21:58.469 --> 00:22:01.093
In general, using underlines
you could do a background

437
00:22:01.093 --> 00:22:04.355
but you need to make sure
it has sufficient contrast

438
00:22:04.355 --> 00:22:06.952
to what's around it
and some other element

439
00:22:06.952 --> 00:22:11.039
to help identify... is preferred.

440
00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:13.698
This is a big one

441
00:22:13.698 --> 00:22:17.280
is to, and again you'll
see this everywhere.

442
00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:20.799
I'm sure we've all written
link text like this.

443
00:22:20.799 --> 00:22:25.433
Avoid generic phrases
like "click here"or "read more" 

444
00:22:25.433 --> 00:22:29.038
because link text
should describe the link

445
00:22:29.038 --> 00:22:34.328
and not rely on the
surrounding text for context.

446
00:22:34.328 --> 00:22:39.600
A link should let you know
where it's going to take you

447
00:22:39.600 --> 00:22:43.039
just by having the link text,
that's the ideal.

448
00:22:43.039 --> 00:22:45.657
These again, they're
little things that you can do

449
00:22:45.657 --> 00:22:47.883
to make a big difference.

450
00:22:47.883 --> 00:22:49.779
Why I say that is 
this is 

451
00:22:49.779 --> 00:22:53.828
the screen reader rotor 
for voiceover.

452
00:22:53.828 --> 00:22:56.064
If you're on a site
that just uses "click here",

453
00:22:56.064 --> 00:22:59.353
you can navigate by links
and see that structure,

454
00:22:59.353 --> 00:23:02.617
it's just going to say
"click here" on everything.

455
00:23:02.617 --> 00:23:04.901
It takes those links
out of context

456
00:23:04.901 --> 00:23:06.936
and there's no relation.

457
00:23:06.936 --> 00:23:10.535
Imagine instead someone 
used those links as, 

458
00:23:10.535 --> 00:23:12.720
"Buy Now" or 
"Upcoming Events" or 

459
00:23:12.720 --> 00:23:15.779
"all of our available properties."

460
00:23:15.779 --> 00:23:18.075
With these things, 
you don't even know 

461
00:23:18.075 --> 00:23:19.854
what site you're necessarily on

462
00:23:19.854 --> 00:23:22.963
but you can get an idea
of what's going to happen

463
00:23:22.963 --> 00:23:25.767
when you click that
just from the link itself,

464
00:23:25.767 --> 00:23:28.960
from the text itself.

465
00:23:29.360 --> 00:23:33.254
Colors: 
The last presentation

466
00:23:33.254 --> 00:23:36.542
did a great job of going over
all the details of that

467
00:23:36.542 --> 00:23:39.919
so I won't spend
too much time here.

468
00:23:39.919 --> 00:23:44.713
A few basic things to 
keep in mind are color contrast

469
00:23:44.713 --> 00:23:48.138
and it says on the slide, 
"Can people read the text?"

470
00:23:48.138 --> 00:23:51.314
and the text fades out 
into that blue

471
00:23:51.314 --> 00:23:53.544
that matches the 
blue background.

472
00:23:53.544 --> 00:23:56.186
It makes it 
really hard to read. 

473
00:23:56.186 --> 00:23:58.020
We're going 
for a minimum.

474
00:23:58.020 --> 00:24:00.341
The contrast color checkers,
if you Google them,

475
00:24:00.341 --> 00:24:03.097
they're pretty easy
to come across.

476
00:24:03.097 --> 00:24:05.188
Contrast ratio,
the minimum

477
00:24:05.188 --> 00:24:08.606
that you'd want to shoot for
is a 4.5 of contrast

478
00:24:08.606 --> 00:24:11.487
between the foreground
and background. 

479
00:24:11.487 --> 00:24:15.881
Ideally you're gonna 
get closer to 7:1,

480
00:24:15.881 --> 00:24:17.904
especially for body text.

481
00:24:17.904 --> 00:24:22.964
Other UI elements
can be closer to 4.5,

482
00:24:22.964 --> 00:24:25.191
something to remember. 

483
00:24:25.191 --> 00:24:29.840
As well as, the last 
presentation mentioned this

484
00:24:29.840 --> 00:24:33.679
to not rely on color only
and here's an example of that.

485
00:24:33.679 --> 00:24:35.865
We have a form here.

486
00:24:35.865 --> 00:24:38.284
It says first name
and has a red check

487
00:24:38.284 --> 00:24:41.200
and then last name has 
my last name Jones in it

488
00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:43.365
with a green check 
and that has 

489
00:24:43.365 --> 00:24:45.726
the no color blindness 
presentation.

490
00:24:45.726 --> 00:24:49.126
If you look at
the same thing

491
00:24:49.126 --> 00:24:53.196
with a red blindness, 
both those check marks

492
00:24:53.196 --> 00:24:55.747
start to become
a lot more similar

493
00:24:55.747 --> 00:25:00.000
and there's not a strong
difference between them.

494
00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:03.179
I use the check mark here
because people can sometimes

495
00:25:03.179 --> 00:25:08.239
use that for both positive correct
and the negative incorrect.

496
00:25:08.239 --> 00:25:12.219
You can fix things like this
by adding some text

497
00:25:12.219 --> 00:25:14.027
to describe it 
because similarly 

498
00:25:14.027 --> 00:25:15.569
icons shouldn't be standalone.

499
00:25:15.569 --> 00:25:19.274
There should always be
some text that supports that.

500
00:25:19.274 --> 00:25:22.000
In this instance
for the empty field,

501
00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.597
we just say your 
first name is required.

502
00:25:24.597 --> 00:25:26.480
You can see
on both those

503
00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:30.480
with colorblindness
and with no colorblindness,

504
00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:32.096
you get that text to
help support 

505
00:25:32.096 --> 00:25:34.621
and actually tell you 
what's wrong 

506
00:25:34.621 --> 00:25:40.320
which makes it way more 
accessible for everyone.

507
00:25:41.600 --> 00:25:45.279
Just quickly, some
cognitive accessibility tips

508
00:25:45.279 --> 00:25:49.679
is to make things
easier to understand.

509
00:25:49.679 --> 00:25:54.007
Ways you can do that are,
if you have a long paragraph

510
00:25:54.007 --> 00:25:56.096
that has a few points in it

511
00:25:56.096 --> 00:25:58.559
break that up
into bulleted lists.

512
00:25:58.559 --> 00:26:00.311
You can also use 

513
00:26:00.311 --> 00:26:03.919
shorter sentences 
and smaller words.

514
00:26:05.200 --> 00:26:09.799
If highlighting or bolding
the important pieces of text

515
00:26:09.799 --> 00:26:11.332
it is super useful.

516
00:26:11.332 --> 00:26:13.752
Also, useful for skimming

517
00:26:13.752 --> 00:26:15.956
so you can 
get the idea

518
00:26:15.956 --> 00:26:18.159
and take things in
of a larger article

519
00:26:18.159 --> 00:26:21.617
and see the important parts. 

520
00:26:21.617 --> 00:26:24.240
Don't ever use a timer

521
00:26:24.240 --> 00:26:28.480
because one, it puts pressure
on people unnecessarily

522
00:26:28.480 --> 00:26:32.656
and two, there's no reason
or there's rarely a reason

523
00:26:32.656 --> 00:26:35.929
I guess, that you would 
need to limit someone's

524
00:26:35.929 --> 00:26:38.517
access to the content. 

525
00:26:38.517 --> 00:26:42.044
It creates something 
that could be accessible 

526
00:26:42.044 --> 00:26:45.695
and makes it inaccessible 
just by adding a timer 

527
00:26:45.695 --> 00:26:47.448
so please don't use them.

528
00:26:47.448 --> 00:26:49.134
Don't autoplay things.

529
00:26:49.134 --> 00:26:53.495
This is another thing that 
you're taking control away

530
00:26:53.495 --> 00:26:57.343
from the user and 
the only argument

531
00:26:57.343 --> 00:27:00.462
I hear for them is from
the business side of it.

532
00:27:00.462 --> 00:27:03.084
It's not from 
a person saying

533
00:27:03.084 --> 00:27:05.931
I prefer everything
being autoplayed.

534
00:27:05.931 --> 00:27:09.900
We've all been to a website
that has it start autoplaying

535
00:27:09.900 --> 00:27:12.550
and then you don't know
how to turn it off,

536
00:27:12.550 --> 00:27:14.960
so many things that 
can go wrong with it.

537
00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:20.320
So please, 
don't autoplay things.

538
00:27:20.320 --> 00:27:22.615
About evaluating 
for accessibility.

539
00:27:22.615 --> 00:27:25.424
This is going back
to the beginning

540
00:27:25.424 --> 00:27:29.600
when we asked for
some plugins or themes.

541
00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:32.672
How I go over them,
because oftentimes

542
00:27:32.672 --> 00:27:35.411
I'd be in a situation
where I would

543
00:27:35.411 --> 00:27:39.438
